text: A meta-labeling is what's called a supervised training algorithm, a supervised machine learning algorithm. In a supervised training algorithm, you need to have a set of features. These features could be simple technical indicators, could be macroeconomic indicators, it could be fancy big data from the credit card transactions or the satellite imagery. You could have 100 features, you could have a thousand features. They are arranged, you can imagine them as columns on a spreadsheet. The roles are the different traits that your base model makes. The roles might be, okay, today I made three traits. One trait was profitable, next trait is negative, the third trait is negative again. You might have three roles representing three round trips that you made. Of course, you will collect data on maybe thousands of traits that you have done in the past. What is called a target variable, or some people call it label, or other people call it the dependent variable, would be where the target is. Whether that trait in the past was profitable or not. If it's profitable, let's call it one. If it's not profitable, let's call it zero. Based on these hundreds of features, you are trying to predict whether it's going to be one or zero. The one or zero are what is called a meta label by Dr. Di Prado and Dr. Lopez Di Prado. Once the system is trained like that, when you give it a new set of features, let's say today's price. Today's GDP numbers. Today's unemployment number, what not. It will try to generate probability. The label is going to be zero, which means profitable. I'm sorry, where the label will be one, which is indicating profitability, or zero when you expect a loss. Clearly, if the model tells you that it expects a loss, you might hesitate to trade or even you were to trade, you might hesitate to put on the full capital into that trade.
